113
00:06:48,833 --> 00:06:50,155
Basic Questions.

114
00:06:50,155 --> 00:06:52,799
Q: Is quantum computing just hype?

115
00:06:52,799 --> 00:06:56,525
A: No, but expectations need calibration.

116
00:06:56,525 --> 00:07:03,328
Quantum computing is real and making progress, but we're still years away from broad practical applications.

117
00:07:03,328 --> 00:07:11,922
Current machines are like 1950s classical computers - useful for research and specific problems, not general-purpose yet.

118
00:07:11,922 --> 00:07:14,771
Q: Will quantum computers replace my laptop?

119
00:07:14,771 --> 00:07:15,564
A: No.

120
00:07:15,564 --> 00:07:21,970
Quantum computers are good at specific types of problems (optimization, simulation, cryptography).

121
00:07:21,970 --> 00:07:27,775
Your laptop will always be better for everyday tasks like browsing, documents, and videos.

122
00:07:27,775 --> 00:07:31,345
Q: Do I need a physics PhD to learn quantum computing?

123
00:07:31,345 --> 00:07:32,150
A: No.

124
00:07:32,150 --> 00:07:34,999
You need basic linear algebra and programming.

125
00:07:34,999 --> 00:07:40,840
Many successful quantum developers come from computer science, engineering, or math backgrounds.

126
00:07:40,840 --> 00:07:43,052
Physics helps but isn't required.

127
00:07:43,052 --> 00:07:46,297
Q: When will quantum computers break encryption?

128
00:07:46,297 --> 00:07:54,903
A: Current estimates suggest 10-20+ years for breaking strong encryption like RSA-2048.

129
00:07:54,903 --> 00:08:03,737
However, "harvest now, decrypt later" attacks are a concern - organizations should start migrating to post-quantum cryptography now.

130
00:08:03,737 --> 00:08:05,119
Technical Questions.

131
00:08:05,119 --> 00:08:08,821
Q: What's the difference between qubits and classical bits?

132
00:08:08,821 --> 00:08:12,523
A: Classical bits are either 0 or 1.

133
00:08:12,523 --> 00:08:17,487
Qubits can be 0, 1, or both simultaneously (superposition).

134
00:08:17,487 --> 00:08:21,886
This allows quantum computers to process many possibilities at once.

135
00:08:21,886 --> 00:08:24,758
Q: Why do quantum computers need to be so cold?

136
00:08:24,758 --> 00:08:29,963
A: Heat causes vibrations that destroy quantum states (decoherence).

137
00:08:29,963 --> 00:08:38,304
Near absolute zero, atoms barely move, allowing qubits to maintain their quantum properties long enough for calculations.

138
00:08:38,304 --> 00:08:40,504
Q: Can I run quantum programs at home?

139
00:08:40,504 --> 00:08:44,085
A: You can run quantum simulators on your regular computer.

140
00:08:44,085 --> 00:08:51,153
For real quantum hardware, you can access IBM, Amazon, or Microsoft's cloud quantum computers for free.

141
00:08:51,153 --> 00:08:54,494
Q: What programming languages are used for quantum computing?

142
00:08:54,494 --> 00:09:00,143
A: Python is most common, using libraries like: Qiskit (IBM).

